definition.value: A dihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid with hydroxy groups located at positions 3beta and 6beta.
The pyranose form of D-kanosamine.
A hydroxy fatty acid that is palmitic (hexadecanoic) acid substituted with one hydroxy group.
A C27 bile acid that is 5beta-cholest-24-en-26-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3alpha and 7beta.
A member of the class of glucosamines that is D-glucose in which the hydroxy group at C-3 is replaced by an amino group.
A member of the class of flavanones having one or more glycosyl residues attached at unspecified positions.
A primary ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of aldehydo-D-kanosamine(1+).
A primary ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of 3-amino-3-deoxy-D-glucopyranose.
A steroid sulfate that is the 3-O-sulfo derivative of glycochenodeoxycholic acid.
An acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group contains twenty-two carbons with six double bonds and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.
An acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group contains twenty carbons with three double bonds and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.
An acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group contains fifteen carbons with no double bonds and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.

An  lysophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl group contains seventeen carbons and no double bonds. If R1 is an acyl group and R2 is a hydrogen then the molecule is a 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolaminecholine. If R1 is a hydrogen and R2 is an acyl group then the molecule is a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.
A glycero-3-phosphoserine that is sn-glycero-3-phospho-L-serine substituted at position 1 by an octadecyl group.
Any member of the class of isoflavanones with at least one hydroxy substituent.
The N-formimidoyl derivative of L-glutamic acid
Members of the class of isoflavanones with at least one methoxy substituent.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-eicosatetraenoyl (arachidonoyl).
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as 8Z,11Z,14Z,17Z-eicosapentaenoyl (omega-3-arachidonoyl).
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alk-1-enyl and acyl group are specified as (Z)-hexadec-1-enyl and hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) respectively.
A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl and alkyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and hexadecyl respectively.
A straight-chain unsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of (E)-hexadec-2-enoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as 8Z,11Z,14Z,17Z-eicosapentaenoyl (omega-3-arachidonoyl).
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as 4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z-docosahexaenoyl.

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained from 3-amino-3-deoxy-6-O-phosphono-D-glucopyranose by removal of both protons from the phosphate group and protonation of the amino group. The major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as 4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z-docosahexaenoyl.

A carbotricyclic compound obtained from the pathogenic fungi Aspergillus fumigatus and Neosartorya fischeri following activation of their polycyclic polyketide prenyltransferase (pcPTase)-containing silent clusters. It exhibits T-cell antiproliferative activity with an IC50 of 3 muM, suggesting a possible physiological role as an immunosuppressive agent.
An organic disulfide that results from the formal oxidative dimerisation of benzyl thiol.
An L-alpha-amino acid that is L-dopa carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 6.
An organofluorine compound that is  bisphenol A with its methyl hydrogens replaced by fluorines.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the primary amino groups of kanamycin C.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the primary amino groups of kanamycin X.
A quadruply-charged organic cation arising from protonation of the four amino groups of 2'-oxokanamycin A; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid obtained by protonation of the amino group of sphinga-4E,8E-dienine.
A N-acylsphinganine-1-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is pentadecanoyl.
A cyclic dipeptide that is brevianamide F (cyclo-L-Trp-L-Pro) substituted at position 2 on the indole ring by a prenyl group.
A cyclic dipeptide that is brevianamide F (cyclo-L-Trp-L-Pro) substituted at positions 2 and 6 on the indole ring by prenyl and methoxy groups respectively.
A cyclic dipeptide that is brevianamide F (cyclo-L-Trp-L-Pro) substituted at positions 2 and 6 on the indole ring by prenyl and hydroxy groups respectively.
An organic heteropentacyclic compound that is a mycotoxic indole alkaloid produced by several fungi. A potent and specific inhibitor of the breast cancer resistance protein multidrug transporter.
An indole alkaloid  that is fumitremorgin C substituted at positions 12 and 13 by hydroxy groups.
An organic heterohexacyclic compound that is a mycotoxic indole alkaloid isolated from Penicillium and Aspergillus species.
An organic heterohexacyclic compound that is a mycotoxic indole alkaloid obtained by prenylation of the 10-hydroxy group of verruculogen.
An organic heteropentacyclic compound that is a mycotoxic indole alkaloid, consisting of fumitremorgin C lacking the 9-methoxy substituent.
An agonist that binds to and activates aryl hydrocarbon receptors (AhRs).
A kanamycin obtained by dehydrogenation at position 2' of kanamycin A.
A glycine derivative that is glycine with a tertiary butyl group at position 2.
Any inhibitor of breast cancer resistance protein (ABCG2).
A beta-amino acid that is pentanoic acid substituted at positions 3 and 4 by amino and methyl groups respectively.
Any inhibitor of the biosynthesis of carotenoids.

An EC 1.3.99.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-CH group with other acceptors) inhibitor that interferes with the action of phytoene desaturase (zeta-carotene-forming), EC 1.3.99.29, an enzyme of carotenoid biosynthesis that converts phytoene into zeta-carotene (zeta-carotene) via the symmetrical introduction of two double bonds at the C-11 and C-11' positions of phytoene.
